   319Ôćĺ## Agents
   321Ôćĺ<img src="https://dotenvx.com/assets/img/as2/9.jpg" height="400" alt="dotenvx-as2" align="right"/>
   322Ôćĺ
   323Ôćĺ> Software is changing, and dotenv must change with itÔÇöthat is why I built [agentic secret storage (AS2)](https://dotenvx.com/as2). Agents run code without humans at terminals, so plaintext `.env` files are the wrong primitive.
   324Ôćĺ>
   325Ôćĺ> AS2 is built for autonomous software: encrypted by default, zero console access, and cryptographyÔÇĹfirst delivery that keeps operators out of the loop.
   326Ôćĺ>
   327Ôćĺ> It is backed by [Vestauth](https://github.com/vestauth/vestauth), the trusted, pioneering auth layer for agentsÔÇögiving each agent a cryptographic identity so requests are signed with private keys and verified with public keys. No shared secrets to leak.
   328Ôćĺ>
   329Ôćĺ> It's what I'm using now. - [motdotla](https://mot.la)
   330Ôćĺ
   331Ôćĺ### Quickstart
   333ÔćĺInstall vestauth and initialize your agent.
   334Ôćĺ
   335Ôćĺ```bash
   336Ôćĺnpm i -g vestauth
   337Ôćĺ
   338Ôćĺvestauth agent init
   339Ôćĺ```
   340Ôćĺ
   341ÔćĺYour agent `set`s secrets with a simple `curl` endpoint:
   342Ôćĺ
   343Ôćĺ```bash
   344Ôćĺvestauth agent curl -X POST https://as2.dotenvx.com/set -d '{"KEY":"value"}'
   345Ôćĺ```
   346Ôćĺ
   347ÔćĺAnd your agent `get`s secrets with a simple `curl` endpoint:
   348Ôćĺ
   349Ôćĺ```bash
   350Ôćĺvestauth agent curl "https://as2.dotenvx.com/get?key=KEY"
   351Ôćĺ```
   352Ôćĺ
   353ÔćĺThat's it! This new primitive unlocks secrets access for agents without human-in-the-loop, oauth flows, or API keys. It's the future for agents.
   354Ôćĺ
   355Ôćĺ&nbsp;
   356Ôćĺ
   357Ôćĺ## FAQ
   359Ôćĺ<details><summary>Should I commit my `.env` file?</summary><br/>
   360Ôćĺ
   361ÔćĺNo.
   362Ôćĺ
   363ÔćĺUnless you encrypt it with [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx). Then we recommend you do.
   364Ôćĺ
   365Ôćĺ</details>
   366Ôćĺ<details><summary>What about variable expansion?</summary><br/>
   367Ôćĺ
   368ÔćĺUse [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx).
   369Ôćĺ
   370Ôćĺ</details>
   371Ôćĺ<details><summary>Should I have multiple `.env` files?</summary><br/>
   372Ôćĺ
   373ÔćĺWe recommend creating one `.env` file per environment. Use `.env` for local/development, `.env.production` for production and so on. This still follows the twelve factor principles as each is attributed individually to its own environment. Avoid custom set ups that work in inheritance somehow (`.env.production` inherits values form `.env` for example). It is better to duplicate values if necessary across each `.env.environment` file.
   374Ôćĺ
   375Ôćĺ> In a twelve-factor app, env vars are granular controls, each fully orthogonal to other env vars. They are never grouped together as ÔÇťenvironmentsÔÇŁ, but instead are independently managed for each deploy. This is a model that scales up smoothly as the app naturally expands into more deploys over its lifetime.
   376Ôćĺ>
   377Ôćĺ> ÔÇô [The Twelve-Factor App](http://12factor.net/config)
   378Ôćĺ
   379ÔćĺAdditionally, we recommend using [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) to encrypt and manage these.
   380Ôćĺ
   381Ôćĺ</details>
   382Ôćĺ
   383Ôćĺ<details><summary>How do I use dotenv with `import`?</summary><br/>
   384Ôćĺ
   385ÔćĺSimply..
   386Ôćĺ
   387Ôćĺ```javascript
   388Ôćĺ// index.mjs (ESM)
   389Ôćĺimport 'dotenv/config' // see https://github.com/motdotla/dotenv#how-do-i-use-dotenv-with-import
   390Ôćĺimport express from 'express'
   391Ôćĺ```
   392Ôćĺ
   393ÔćĺA little background..
   394Ôćĺ
      ÔćĺÔÇŽ
   579Ôćĺ## Docs
   581ÔćĺDotenv exposes four functions:
   582Ôćĺ
   583Ôćĺ* `config`
   584Ôćĺ* `parse`
   585Ôćĺ* `populate`
   586Ôćĺ
   587Ôćĺ### Config
   589Ôćĺ`config` will read your `.env` file, parse the contents, assign it to
   590Ôćĺ[`process.env`](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest/api/process.html#process_process_env),
   591Ôćĺand return an Object with a `parsed` key containing the loaded content or an `error` key if it failed.
   592Ôćĺ
   593Ôćĺ```js
   594Ôćĺconst result = dotenv.config()
   595Ôćĺ
   596Ôćĺif (result.error) {
   597Ôćĺ  throw result.error
   598Ôćĺ}
   599Ôćĺ
   600Ôćĺconsole.log(result.parsed)
   601Ôćĺ```
   602Ôćĺ
   603ÔćĺYou can additionally, pass options to `config`.
   604Ôćĺ
   605Ôćĺ#### Options
   607Ôćĺ##### path
   609ÔćĺDefault: `path.resolve(process.cwd(), '.env')`
   610Ôćĺ
   611ÔćĺSpecify a custom path if your file containing environment variables is located elsewhere.
   612Ôćĺ
   613Ôćĺ```js
   614Ôćĺrequire('dotenv').config({ path: '/custom/path/to/.env' })
   615Ôćĺ```
   616Ôćĺ
   617ÔćĺBy default, `config` will look for a file called .env in the current working directory.
   618Ôćĺ
   619ÔćĺPass in multiple files as an array, and they will be parsed in order and combined with `process.env` (or `option.processEnv`, if set). The first value set for a variable will win, unless the `options.override` flag is set, in which case the last value set will win.  If a value already exists in `process.env` and the `options.override` flag is NOT set, no changes will be made to that value. 
   620Ôćĺ
   621Ôćĺ```js  
   622Ôćĺrequire('dotenv').config({ path: ['.env.local', '.env'] })
   623Ôćĺ```
   624Ôćĺ
   625Ôćĺ##### quiet
   627ÔćĺDefault: `false`
   628Ôćĺ
   629ÔćĺSuppress runtime logging message.
   630Ôćĺ
   631Ôćĺ```js
   632Ôćĺ// index.js
   633Ôćĺrequire('dotenv').config({ quiet: false }) // change to true to suppress
   634Ôćĺconsole.log(`Hello ${process.env.HELLO}`)
   635Ôćĺ```
   636Ôćĺ
   637Ôćĺ```ini
   638Ôćĺ# .env
   639ÔćĺHELLO=World
   640Ôćĺ```
   641Ôćĺ
   642Ôćĺ```sh
   643Ôćĺ$ node index.js
   644Ôćĺ[dotenv@17.0.0] injecting env (1) from .env
   645ÔćĺHello World
   646Ôćĺ```
   647Ôćĺ
   648Ôćĺ##### encoding
   650ÔćĺDefault: `utf8`
   651Ôćĺ
   652ÔćĺSpecify the encoding of your file containing environment variables.
   653Ôćĺ
   654Ôćĺ```js
   655Ôćĺrequire('dotenv').config({ encoding: 'latin1' })
   656Ôćĺ```
   657Ôćĺ
   658Ôćĺ##### debug
   660ÔćĺDefault: `false`
   661Ôćĺ
   662ÔćĺTurn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   663Ôćĺ
   664Ôćĺ```js
   665Ôćĺrequire('dotenv').config({ debug: process.env.DEBUG })
   666Ôćĺ```
   667Ôćĺ
   668Ôćĺ##### override
   670ÔćĺDefault: `false`
   671Ôćĺ
   672ÔćĺOverride any environment variables that have already been set on your machine with values from your .env file(s). If multiple files have been provided in `option.path` the override will also be used as each file is combined with the next. Without `override` being set, the first value wins. With `override` set the last value wins. 
   673Ôćĺ
   674Ôćĺ```js
   675Ôćĺrequire('dotenv').config({ override: true })
   676Ôćĺ```
   677Ôćĺ
   678Ôćĺ##### processEnv
   680ÔćĺDefault: `process.env`
   681Ôćĺ
   682ÔćĺSpecify an object to write your environment variables to. Defaults to `process.env` environment variables.
   683Ôćĺ
   684Ôćĺ```js
   685Ôćĺconst myObject = {}
   686Ôćĺrequire('dotenv').config({ processEnv: myObject })
   687Ôćĺ
   688Ôćĺconsole.log(myObject) // values from .env
   689Ôćĺconsole.log(process.env) // this was not changed or written to
   690Ôćĺ```
   691Ôćĺ
   692Ôćĺ### Parse
   694ÔćĺThe engine which parses the contents of your file containing environment
   695Ôćĺvariables is available to use. It accepts a String or Buffer and will return
   696Ôćĺan Object with the parsed keys and values.
   697Ôćĺ
   698Ôćĺ```js
   699Ôćĺconst dotenv = require('dotenv')
   700Ôćĺconst buf = Buffer.from('BASIC=basic')
   701Ôćĺconst config = dotenv.parse(buf) // will return an object
   702Ôćĺconsole.log(typeof config, config) // object { BASIC : 'basic' }
   703Ôćĺ```
   704Ôćĺ
   705Ôćĺ#### Options
   707Ôćĺ##### debug
   709ÔćĺDefault: `false`
   710Ôćĺ
   711ÔćĺTurn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   712Ôćĺ
   713Ôćĺ```js
   714Ôćĺconst dotenv = require('dotenv')
   715Ôćĺconst buf = Buffer.from('hello world')
   716Ôćĺconst opt = { debug: true }
   717Ôćĺconst config = dotenv.parse(buf, opt)
   718Ôćĺ// expect a debug message because the buffer is not in KEY=VAL form
   719Ôćĺ```
   720Ôćĺ
   721Ôćĺ### Populate
   723ÔćĺThe engine which populates the contents of your .env file to `process.env` is available for use. It accepts a target, a source, and options. This is useful for power users who want to supply their own objects.
   724Ôćĺ
   725ÔćĺFor example, customizing the source:
   726Ôćĺ
   727Ôćĺ```js
   728Ôćĺconst dotenv = require('dotenv')
   729Ôćĺconst parsed = { HELLO: 'world' }
   730Ôćĺ
   731Ôćĺdotenv.populate(process.env, parsed)
   732Ôćĺ
   733Ôćĺconsole.log(process.env.HELLO) // world
   734Ôćĺ```
   735Ôćĺ
   736ÔćĺFor example, customizing the source AND target:
   737Ôćĺ
   738Ôćĺ```js
   739Ôćĺconst dotenv = require('dotenv')
   740Ôćĺconst parsed = { HELLO: 'universe' }
   741Ôćĺconst target = { HELLO: 'world' } // empty object
   742Ôćĺ
   743Ôćĺdotenv.populate(target, parsed, { override: true, debug: true })
   744Ôćĺ
   745Ôćĺconsole.log(target) // { HELLO: 'universe' }
   746Ôćĺ```
   747Ôćĺ
   748Ôćĺ#### options
   750Ôćĺ##### Debug
   752ÔćĺDefault: `false`
   753Ôćĺ
   754ÔćĺTurn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being populated as you expect.
   755Ôćĺ
   756Ôćĺ##### override
   758ÔćĺDefault: `false`
   759Ôćĺ
   760ÔćĺOverride any environment variables that have already been set.
   761Ôćĺ
   762Ôćĺ&nbsp;
   763Ôćĺ
   764Ôćĺ## CHANGELOG
   766ÔćĺSee [CHANGELOG.md](CHANGELOG.md)
   767Ôćĺ
   768Ôćĺ&nbsp;
   769Ôćĺ
   770Ôćĺ## Who's using dotenv?
   772Ôćĺ[These npm modules depend on it.](https://www.npmjs.com/browse/depended/dotenv)
   773Ôćĺ
   774ÔćĺProjects that expand it often use the [keyword "dotenv" on npm](https://www.npmjs.com/search?q=keywords:dotenv).
